How to Think About Blackbird
There are a few different ways to think about Blackbird. They=E2=80=99re al=
l connected, but it=E2=80=99s worth unpacking them separately before bringi=
ng them back together.=C2=A0=C2=A0
One way to think about Blackbird is from the industry perspective: as a too=
l to help restaurants drive better unit economics through payments, loyalty=
, and customer insights.=C2=A0
A second way to think about Blackbird is from the diner perspective: as a w=
ay to discover=C2=A0somewhere to eat and get magical, personalized dining e=
xperiences that scale alongside your loyalty.
Another way to think about Blackbird is as a business itself: as an onchain=
 AmEx, similar in many ways and different in a few important ones.=C2=A0
A fourth way to think about Blackbird is as a blockchain network: as a dece=
ntralized platform that enables new forms of value creation and distributio=
n in the restaurant ecosystem, and potentially, beyond it.=C2=A0
It=E2=80=99s all of those things, but to understand them, we need to start =
by understanding the restaurant business.
The Restaurant Business
Restaurants are one of those things that we don=E2=80=99t really want to th=
ink about as a business. Businesses need to make trade-offs. We don=E2=80=
=99t want restaurants to make trade-offs. We want great food and great serv=
ice every time we walk in the door, because from our perspective, restauran=
ts are an occasion. They=E2=80=99re the rare chance to be taken care of, tr=
eated like royalty, served. A little treat.=C2=A0
But, alas, restaurants are a business, and their business model directly im=
pacts the level of service they=E2=80=99re able to provide.=C2=A0
When Kevin Kwok wrote Aligning Business Models to Markets [ https://substac=
k.com/redirect/dc97e590-078a-4912-908b-86526dbd2abb?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.=
gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] in 2019, he used a restaurant=
 group, Danny Meyer=E2=80=99s Union Square Hospitality Group (USHG), as his=
 primary example.=C2=A0
USHG is undoubtedly one of the great success stories in the restaurant indu=
stry. Meyer made Union Square what it is today. The Modern, Union Square Ca=
fe, Manhatta, Gramercy Tavern, and ci siamo rank consistently among New Yor=
kers=E2=80=99 favorite places to eat. Shake Shack, which spun out of USHG, =
has a $3.4 billion market cap. In such a challenging industry, USHG=E2=80=
=99s consistency stands out.=C2=A0
How does Danny do it? Kwok explains: =E2=80=9CIn his business memoir Settin=
g the Table [ https://substack.com/redirect/ac23d615-8943-49ce-873a-fd541e0=
81406?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ],=
 Meyer attributes his outsized success to an uncompromising focus on employ=
ees that leads to differentiated service.=E2=80=9D
So, Kwok asks, =E2=80=9CIf Danny Meyer=E2=80=99s employee-first approach is=
 so effective, why haven=E2=80=99t we seen more restaurant groups adopting =
it faster? Or even more service-first approaches?=E2=80=9D And answers, =E2=
=80=9CProviding a high level of service is a choice that must be supported =
by your business model.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
I highly recommend reading the whole essay [ https://substack.com/redirect/=
dc97e590-078a-4912-908b-86526dbd2abb?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNu=
aMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], but the long and short of it is that a high=
 level of service requires investing in training employees, training employ=
ees is expensive, and most restaurants can=E2=80=99t afford to make the inv=
estment because employee churn is too high, ranging from 50% to 110% annual=
ly. Once you=E2=80=99ve paid to train someone, they=E2=80=99re gone. USHG, =
however, can afford to train its employees, because the group operates rest=
aurants from fast casual up to fine dining and can therefore offer its empl=
oyees a clear career progression. You could start behind the counter at Sha=
ke Shack and end up managing the Modern.=C2=A0
Because employees stick around longer, USHG can afford to invest more in tr=
aining them, which creates the differentiated service that makes USHG=E2=80=
=99s restaurants so good and allows the group to continue to open new resta=
urants and create even more career opportunities for its employees.=C2=A0
The takeaway is that the quality of a restaurant=E2=80=99s experience, and =
therefore its profitability, is a function of its business model.=C2=A0
But why, Kwok wonders, did something like USHG take off now when you could =
have made a similar case at any point in the restaurant industry=E2=80=99s =
centuries-old history?=C2=A0
In the old days, people didn=E2=80=99t have much choice. They went to the l=
ocal restaurant because it was local. The restaurant industry was supply dr=
iven. Now, consumers have hundreds of choices and dozens of internet source=
s to discover them, =E2=80=9Cand being a place consumers want to come back =
to becomes more important.=E2=80=9D The restaurant industry is now demand d=
riven. As Kwok writes:=C2=A0
These shifts to the demand side of the industry have made restaurants care =
more about quality of service. Customers are able to go anywhere they want,=
 so great restaurants are better able to retain customers.
So great service is necessary in today=E2=80=99s restaurant market, but gre=
at service requires a level of investment that most independent restaurants=
 can=E2=80=99t afford given employee turnover, but really given the fact th=
at most independent restaurants operate at razor thin profit margins.=C2=A0
Earlier, we discussed the fact that restaurant industry average margins hav=
e dropped from 20% to 4%. That=E2=80=99s thin. But high-level numbers are s=
terile, so I read a couple of restaurant owners=E2=80=99 breakdowns of thei=
r margins to get a better understanding of what it=E2=80=99s like on the gr=
ound.=C2=A0
In The Financial Reality of Restaurant Ownership [ https://substack.com/red=
irect/ec66bf51-ce2c-47cb-82b2-0b5a14e2a23e?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7Gn=
