t in payments and loyalty. He understood how powerful that business model i=
s, and how restaurant and hospitality is dependent on that business but doe=
sn=E2=80=99t have a lot of influence on it. He thought rebuilding the busin=
ess onchain with a network that the restaurant owners could be owners in wa=
s very timely.=C2=A0
There are similarities between the two businesses, and important difference=
s.=C2=A0
AmEx has built a $170 billion juggernaut on the back of a closed loop loyal=
ty and payments system, in which it is both the issuer and merchant acquire=
r. Its flywheel looks something like this:=C2=A0
AmEx charges higher fees (2.5-3%) than Visa or Mastercard (~2%).=C2=A0
High fees allow AmEx to offer generous rewards, attracting affluent custome=
rs.
Affluent customers drive high transaction volumes, justifying the fees to m=
erchants.
High volumes generate more points, increasing customer loyalty and spend.
Increased loyalty and spend attract more merchants, expanding acceptance.
Wider acceptance drives more transactions, and the cycle continues.
Blackbird, if it succeeds, will look like AmEx in a funhouse mirror:=C2=A0
Blackbird charges lower fees (2%) than traditional restaurant payment syste=
ms (3-4%).=C2=A0
Lower fees attract more restaurants to the network.=C2=A0
Restaurants use $FLY rewards to attract more diners to the network.
Those diners drive volumes, incentivizing more restaurants to join the netw=
ork.
High volumes drive more $FLY points, increasing customer loyalty and spend.
Increased loyalty and spend attract more restaurants, expanding acceptance.
Wider acceptance drives more transactions, and the cycle continues.=C2=A0=
=C2=A0
There=E2=80=99s another wrinkle, which I haven=E2=80=99t mentioned. While $=
FLY is meant to maintain a stable value or a set exchange rate, usage of $F=
LY earns both diners and restaurants ownership in the network, via Blackbir=
d=E2=80=99s second token: $F2. The more $FLY you hold and spend (as a diner=
) or hold and receive (as a restaurant), the more ownership you earn.
What I like about Blackbird=E2=80=99s approach is that ownership is seconda=
ry to experience. It doesn=E2=80=99t kick off the flywheel, it should just =
make the one it has going spin faster by providing an additional incentive =
to both diners and restaurants.=C2=A0
That Blackbird is giving control to restaurants and their customers speaks =
to a key contrast in approach between AmEx and Blackbird:=C2=A0
AmEx=E2=80=99s value is derived from its closed loop payments system at all=
 merchants; Blackbird=E2=80=99s is derived from its open system focused on =
a specific type of merchant.=C2=A0
Over time, other industries might build vertical-specific products that tap=
 into $FLY and $F2, expanding the usefulness of the rewards and the size of=
 the ecosystem.=C2=A0
But Blackbird Labs itself is specifically focused on restaurants, and given=
 its business model, the alignment is clear.=C2=A0
Blackbird needs to make it as easy as possible for restaurants to provide g=
reat experiences using Blackbird=E2=80=99s tools. Those great experiences d=
rive more volume to restaurants, which increasingly gets transacted on Blac=
kbird Pay. Blackbird takes 2% of all of that volume, and is able to capture=
 more as net revenue the more widely $FLY is used.=C2=A0
Great experience =E2=86=92 more volume =E2=86=92 more profit.=C2=A0
True for restaurants, true for Blackbird, and possible, in part, because of=
 crypto.
Crypto Fixes This
We=E2=80=99ve talked about crypto very little thus far. Blackbird=E2=80=99s=
 membership cards are NFTs, its loyalty token is $FLY, and network particip=
ants can earn ownership in the network with $F2, but we=E2=80=99ve focused =
on what those different products do for restaurants and their customers, no=
t on the nitty gritty of the tokens themselves.=C2=A0
That is a great thing.
Blackbird is one of the first =E2=80=9Ccrypto=E2=80=9D apps that=E2=80=99s =
gotten adoption from mainstream users and businesses who might not have any=
 idea that they=E2=80=99re using a =E2=80=9Ccrypto=E2=80=9D app. When I ask=
ed Ben why he thinks that is, he pointed to two reasons:
People love restaurants. =E2=80=9CThey=E2=80=99re hardwired into our habits=
=2E They spark joy. If we situate ourse=
lves in the middle of restaurants, we=
=E2=80=99ll naturally make consumers happy.=E2=80=9D
Building a magical product, blockchain or otherwise: =E2=80=9CThe key to ad=
option is building products that consumers love. It has nothing to do with =
crypto, per se.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
But, having built traditional software products, Ben chose to bring crypto =
into the mix at Blackbird, despite the regulatory complexity and technical =
challenges. This is someone who doesn=E2=80=99t need to work after selling =
two companies, who is dedicated to helping the restaurant industry, and who=
 wouldn=E2=80=99t have built on blockchain rails if it didn=E2=80=99t serve=
 that goal.=C2=A0
So why bring crypto into it?=C2=A0
Last November, in Blockchains as Platforms [ https://substack.com/redirect/=
3b85a4d3-59d4-4919-95fa-a1b536bffc6e?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNu=
aMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], I argued that blockchains are just platform=
s that offer some unique benefits and come with certain drawbacks, and that=
 as the infrastructure improved and those drawbacks were eliminated, more d=
evelopers would build onchain.=C2=A0
When transactions cost $50 each and take minutes to settle, or customers ha=
ve to deal with the complexity of setting up a wallet and signing a transac=
tion to use a product, a lot of consumer developers would decide that the t=
rade-off wasn=E2=80=99t worth it. =E2=80=9CBut,=E2=80=9D I wrote, =E2=80=9C=
With cheaper, faster transactions and UX improvements, those products start=
 to make sense.=E2=80=9D
Blackbird was actually the example I used in that piece.=C2=A0
You couldn=E2=80=99t have built Blackbird onchain even five years ago. That=
=E2=80=99s obvious. Which means that you couldn=E2=80=99t have built a prod=
uct like Blackbird even five years ago. That=E2=80=99s less obvious, but mo=
re important.=C2=A0
Blackbird works because it=E2=80=99s able to perform like a normal consumer=
 app while doing things that a normal consumer app can=E2=80=99t.=C2=A0
Let=E2=80=99s dive into a little bit about how Blackbird is structured unde=
r the hood, courtesy of the new Flypaper [ https://substack.com/redirect/62=
13f187-3bf4-4563-bb0c-f8f896789887?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaM=
ZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], to understand why and how.=C2=A0
Earlier, I mentioned that Blackbird=E2=80=99s restaurant membership cards a=
re NFTs. They=E2=80=99re currently the only part of the app that=E2=80=99s =
onchain, and it=E2=80=99s not very important that they=E2=80=99re onchain. =
For now, they=E2=80=99re non-transferrable (=E2=80=9Cwe don=E2=80=99t think=
 your identity is transferable [ https://substack.com/redirect/e8c0e61a-8a6=
5-4a15-a616-9d4dba55e30b?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKb=
qOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]=E2=80=9D) and can only be used within the Blackbird app.=
 They could just as well be an entry in Blackbird=E2=80=99s database, for n=
ow, aside from the fact that if Blackbird disappeared tomorrow, I could wal=
k into Gjelina and show them that I do own my House Account NFT.=C2=A0
$FLY tokens do exist as entries in Blackbird=E2=80=99s database, for now. W=
hen you check-in to a restaurant that offers $FLY for check-ins, Blackbird =
simply moves $FLY from the restaurant=E2=80=99s allocation to your account =
in its database. When you use $FLY to settle your tab with Blackbird Pay, i=
t simply moves it from your account=E2=80=99s to the restaurant=E2=80=99s i=
n its database.=C2=A0
Going forward, $FLY will be used as an on-platform rewards and payments tok=
en, and restaurants will be able to exchange $FLY with Blackbird at a prett=
y steady exchange rate. It won=E2=80=99t be tradeable, transferable, or red=
eemable for cash outside of the app. You won=E2=80=99t be able to get rich =
speculating on $FLY.=C2=A0
Blackbird users have speculated that, in addition to serving as a reward an=
d payments token, $FLY would also serve as the gas token and representation=
 of ownership in the network once it moved onchain. That is not the case.=
=C2=A0
Instead, the Flypaper [ https://substack.com/redirect/6213f187-3bf4-4563-bb=
0c-f8f896789887?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8=
ExkRNpU ] introduces a new token, $F2, which will serve as the gas and gove=
rnance token for the network. The network itself will be a Layer 3, Flynet,=
 built on top of Coinbase=E2=80=99s Base L2 (which itself is built on top o=
f Ethereum). You don=E2=80=99t need to understand all of that, just that it=
 means a couple of things:
Very fast, cheap transactions. You won=E2=80=99t notice anything different =
than using a normal consumer app, and Blackbird Labs will cover a lot of th=
e fees.=C2=A0
Other Apps Can Build on Flynet. If someone wanted to start a Blackbird for =
airlines, as a dumb example, they could build it on Flynet and tap into $FL=
Y for rewards and payments, and $F2 for gas.=C2=A0
There will be a relationship between $FLY and $F2. When the chain launches,=
 all $FLY balances that exist in Blackbird=E2=80=99s database will be moved=
 onchain into users=E2=80=99 Blackbird spending wallets on a 1:1 basis.=C2=
=A0
$F2 will be allocated to both diners and restaurants based on their $FLY th=
roughput =E2=80=93=C2=A0 the amount of $FLY they hold plus the amount of $F=
LY they=E2=80=99ve burned by spending or redeeming rewards =E2=80=93 divide=
d by the total $FLY throughput on the network. If you somehow hold or have =
used 10% of the $FLY on the network in a given period, you get 10% of that =
period=E2=80=99s $F2 allocation.=C2=A0
This is a simple and beautiful mechanism for distributing ownership in the =
network, and one of the reasons that Blackbird couldn=E2=80=99t have been b=
uilt offchain.
First, network participants (mainly diners and restaurants) will receive 25=
1 million of the 500 million total $F2 tokens, which means they=E2=80=99ll =
own and control a little over half the network.
Second, because $F2 allocation within that 251 million tokens is measured b=
y $FLY throughput, the restaurants and diners that are most active in the n=
etwork will get more ownership of the network.=C2=A0
Third, restaurants should naturally earn more than diners given that most p=
eople can only eat at one restaurant per night, and most restaurants can se=
rve hundreds of people per night.=C2=A0
Fourth, it incentivizes diners and restaurants to join the network and be a=
ctive early. Since allocations are based on individual throughput over tota=
l network throughput, it will be easier to earn more $F2 early. It=E2=80=99=
s an elegant way to get over the marketplace cold start problem.=C2=A0
And finally, because restaurants can reward diners with the $FLY it receive=
s from Blackbird Labs in ways they believe will help the restaurant, and be=
cause restaurants are physical, it will be impossible for bots to come in a=
nd sybil attack the network to steal all of the tokens. Any bot that wants =
to make an off-peak reservation at Principe, physically check-in, spend $50=
0 with friends, and settle the tab in $FLY to maximize their $FLY rewards i=
s welcome to try.=C2=A0
(Side note: I=E2=80=99d love to see the option to book hard-to-get reservat=
ions with $FLY.)
Crypto makes diner and restaurant ownership of the network possible. It als=
o makes instant, practically-zero-fee payments via $FLY on Flynet possible.=
 Those are core components of what makes Blackbird special.=C2=A0
Restaurants and diners don=E2=80=99t need to spend one second thinking abou=
t crypto or how any of it works behind the scenes.=C2=A0
As a restaurant, it=E2=80=99s worth thinking hard about how to design a loy=
alty program that maximizes profitability, encourages the use of Blackbird =
Pay, and increases throughput. They might need to learn a little bit about =
digital acquisition and retention tactics, but they don=E2=80=99t need to k=
now anything about L2s or L3s.
As a diner, you just need to show up, check-in, enjoy, and leave. The same =
way some people work hard to maximize their credit card points or airline m=
iles, or set up bots to snipe restaurant reservations [ https://substack.co=
m/redirect/56932a7f-e6eb-4be0-b21a-962551159777?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J=
5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], some people will scheme to maxim=
ize their $FLY. Great. As long as the restaurants develop programs that are=
 good for the restaurant and the network, it=E2=80=99s a win-win. But diner=
s won=E2=80=99t need to know a thing about crypto to get the =E2=80=9Cregul=
ar=E2=80=9D experience at a growing number of restaurants.=C2=A0
Crypto=E2=80=99s infrastructure is finally good enough that all of that can=
 happen quietly and unnoticeably in the background. Jay pointed to two thin=
gs in particular that help power Blackbird=E2=80=99s surprisingly intuitive=
 UX:=C2=A0
Privy [ https://substack.com/redirect/58101e47-f53a-4cc9-893b-b3bc92e7ade7?=
j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] makes =
it easy to embed wallets that users control but don=E2=80=99t need to think=
 about, right in the app.=C2=A0
Base [ https://substack.com/redirect/e24b5c98-0d1d-4371-bd45-966221b69978?j=
=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], Coinba=
se=E2=80=99s EVM-Compatible Layer-2 network, is a cheap, highly performant =
L2 with the trusted reputation and brand of Coinbase. (Since launching in A=
ugust 2023, Base has already made upgrades that make the network cheaper an=
d faster, which should make onchain transactions so smooth that users won=
=E2=80=99t notice when more of Blackbird=E2=80=99s components move onchain)=
=2E=C2=A0
The result is that Blackbird can build a best-in-class consumer app with su=
perpowers. Programmable incentives. Faster, cheaper payments. Restaurant ow=
nership and control.
And it means that others besides Blackbird will be able to build similar pr=
oducts to fix their industries.=C2=A0
Fred Wilson pointed out that being onchain opens up the opportunity to buil=
d an AmEx-like loyalty program where all the loyalty points are onchain.=C2=
=A0
=E2=80=9C$FLY is like a stablecoin. It=E2=80=99s not something like Bitcoin=
 where you buy it and hope it goes to $100k,=E2=80=9D he said. =E2=80=9CBut=
 the idea of taking loyalty points onchain is a big deal.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
Specifically, it will allow any application to embrace $FLY. =E2=80=9CRight=
 now,=E2=80=9D said Fred, =E2=80=9CAmEx and their partners are the only one=
s who can participate in AmEx points. But $FLY is like USDC [ https://subst=
ack.com/redirect/a14a4046-fe24-4a56-a00e-50fc7d65278e?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3Qif=
Q.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]: hopefully, in time, any de=
veloper will be able to launch something that supports $FLY.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0=
=C2=A0
$FLY may become a rewards and payments token for all sorts of merchants bey=
ond restaurants. If an airline wanted to treat $FLY the same way they treat=
 credit card points, for example, they might be able to do that. If a luxur=
y brand wanted to gate its new drop to only people who hold or have spent a=
 certain amount of $FLY, they might be able to do that, too.=C2=A0
The fun part, as always, is that developers and entrepreneurs will come up =
with much better ideas for how to use $FLY based on their own knowledge of =
what needs fixing, like Ben has for restaurants.=C2=A0
To that end, Jay made a really interesting point about why the a16z team go=
t so excited about Blackbird,=C2=A0 aside from Ben himself. =E2=80=9CWhenev=
er there=E2=80=99s a huge market with a broken business model, it=E2=80=99s=
 a ripe opportunity for someone to try to fix it with crypto.=E2=80=9D=C2=
=A0
Maybe, in Blackbird=E2=80=99s case, crypto really does fixes this, even if =
it does so behind the scenes.
The Way We Eat Now
The future in which Blackbird succeeds just sounds more fun. It=E2=80=99s t=
he world we want to live in, one in which technology is used to create bett=
er in-person human experiences instead of replacing them altogether.=C2=A0
Getting to that future will take a lot of work. As it stands, according to =
@jhackworth=E2=80=99s Dune dashboard [ https://substack.com/redirect/6cb4b4=
1d-8d0a-4c94-a35e-db9fce40f8fb?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjml=
XXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], 38,811 wallets hold Blackbird NFTs and diners hav=
e checked into 142 restaurants, all in NYC. Upside Pizza [ https://substack=
=2Ecom/redirect/1e73502e-2e16-43e4-a41=
a-a6f797f1d070?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.g=
b8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] is the most popular by a wide =
margin.=C2=A0
Getting more restaurants onboard will take time. Restaurants are notoriousl=
y slow to adopt new technologies, and even when the restaurant owner gives =
the green-light, getting restaurant employees to buy-in requires another le=
vel of work.=C2=A0
Blackbird is hard to pull off no matter who you are, but it=E2=80=99s espec=
ially hard if you aren=E2=80=99t Ben Leventhal.=C2=A0
When I asked Ben if he and the team needed to have done Eater and Resy to d=
o Blackbird, he replied, =E2=80=9CKnowing restaurants and understanding how=
 they function, speaking their language, is a humongous advantage that we h=
ave.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
We know, love, and are invested in the industry. We partner with them and h=
ave a long-term track record with them. Day-to-day, we understand how they =
work, how to build tech for them, how they implement, lift of implementatio=
n, and what we can reasonably ask for. We know how to partner with them, ho=
w to engage and say, =E2=80=98What do you need?=E2=80=99, and hear their an=
swer and not take it literally. A lot of the stuff we do well we do well be=
cause we=E2=80=99ve been in the industry a long time.=C2=A0
If Blackbird succeeds, it will succeed because it builds a product that hel=
ps restaurants in the ways that they care about. The technology under the h=
ood is a means, not an end.=C2=A0
Each restaurant is, of course, like all people and all businesses, differen=
t. Some will be excited to try the new thing immediately. Some will take so=
me convincing. But most want to provide their guests with a great experienc=
e that keeps them coming back, and all want more margin.=C2=A0
If Blackbird can deliver on resolving that paradox for its early partners, =
more restaurants will come.=C2=A0
What they do with that margin, just like the loyalty programs they design, =
will be up to the restaurants.=C2=A0
=E2=80=9CToday, for restaurants, it=E2=80=99s existentially unclear what th=
e future holds,=E2=80=9D Ben told me. =E2=80=9CWe want to give them more co=
ntrol of their own destiny.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
Blackbird wants to give restaurants a more sophisticated understanding of t=
heir future based on the actions they take today, and additional margin tha=
t they can spend to act on that understanding in whichever way they think b=
est.=C2=A0
Some will give it back to consumers in the form of prices and perks. Some w=
ill give it to their employees in better benefits, wages, and training. Som=
e will use it to experiment with new things: menu R&D, concept development,=
 CapEx for new locations.=C2=A0
The challenge and the opportunity is that restaurants are beautifully fragm=
ented. That makes it harder to acquire customers and build products that se=
rve their unique needs, but if you can pull that off, if you can give resta=
urants the tools and margin to thrive, it means richer, more fun, more uniq=
ue experiences for everyone to enjoy. It means more opportunities to feel l=
ike a regular in the restaurant that=E2=80=99s just right for you. And it m=
eans local businesses that can thrive without consolidating or homogenizing=
, that can thrive because they=E2=80=99re not consolidated or homogenized.=
=C2=A0
One of my favorite essays of all time is The Way We Live Now [ https://subs=
tack.com/redirect/81efb797-b02e-4929-aa1c-83404be1e70f?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3Qi=
fQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], which Colson Whitehead wr=
ote in The New York Times two months after September 11th. Whitehead writes=
 about New York City as a living, breathing, constantly evolving thing defi=
ned by the closing of old spots and the opening of new ones in their place,=
 but always fixed in time and place by what was there when we first laid ey=
es on it.=C2=A0
No matter how long you have been here, you are a New Yorker the first time =
you say, ''That used to be Munsey's'' or ''That used to be the Tic Toc Loun=
ge.''
You are a New Yorker when what was there before is more real and solid than=
 what is here now.
It=E2=80=99s a defining characteristic of the city, of any city, that our l=
ocal spots, the ones where everybody knows your name, get swallowed up by t=
he struggle and churn. That death and rebirth is what makes a city vibrant.=
 But it would be cool if those spots could ride the wave and evolve with th=
e city and the people who live there. I hope Blackbird helps make that happ=
en.=C2=A0
As for you? Do your part. Go out and eat. Be a regular.
Thanks to Ben, Vanessa, Rachel, Jay, and Fred for telling me the Blackbird =
story!=20
That=E2=80=99s all for today. If you=E2=80=99ve had enough reading and want=
 to start writing, check out Write of Passage [ https://substack.com/redire=
ct/b6662fdb-5d51-4faf-9f16-91d5bff93daf?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_Z=
lNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]. And try to get out and eat local this we=
ek. We=E2=80=99ll be back in your inbox on Friday with a Weekly Dose.=20
Thanks for reading,=20
Packy

