 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>There&=
#8217;s this book I really like, </span><em><a href=3D"https://substack.com=
/redirect/98d4a678-31c5-4196-862d-759aaab4b2db?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5=
T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU" rel style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55)=
; text-decoration: underline;">The City We Became</a></em><span>, in which =
author N.K. Jemisin personifies each of the boroughs with a human avatar. M=
anhattan is a young, brash, multiracial guy. Brooklyn is a middle-aged Blac=
k woman and former rapper. The Bronx is a street-smart Afro-Latina woman. Q=
ueens is an Indian immigrant math student. Staten Island is a sheltered and=
 kinda racist white woman.&#160;</span></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 5=
5); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><strong>If Jem=
isin had personified New York's restaurant scene, she would have chosen Ben=
 Leventhal.</strong><span>&#160;</span></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 5=
5); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>&#8220;B=
en is so New York in a way that&#8217;s hard to articulate,&#8221; </span><=
a href=3D"https://substack.com/redirect/f0618c55-6f8e-4b16-a11b-92a9e364ee5=
d?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU" rel s=
tyle=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); text-decoration: underline;">Jay Drain</a><=
span>, one of the a16z crypto Deal Partners who worked on the Blackbird inv=
estment, told me. &#8220;He just looks like he belongs in a restaurant.&#82=
21;</span></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-hei=
ght: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>Ben grew up in New York. He attended =
Horace Mann, the school that inspired </span><em>Gossip Girl</em><span>. Af=
ter a brief stint outside the city for college, he came back and threw hims=
elf into the intersection of restaurants and technology.&#160;</span></p><p=
 style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margi=
n: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>In 2005, he founded the restaurant discovery blog </s=
pan><strong><a href=3D"https://substack.com/redirect/045ebc5f-38e7-4c97-824=
1-e81f0617e1b1?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8E=
xkRNpU" rel style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); text-decoration: underline;">E=
ater</a></strong><span>. Before Eater, people trusted print guides that bec=
ame dated the second they hit bookshelves, or haughty professional critics =
who reviewed the fancy spots. Eater embraced the internet, and won. He sold=
 it to Vox Media in 2013.&#160;</span></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55=
); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>In 2014, =
he founded the reservation platform, </span><strong><a href=3D"https://subs=
tack.com/redirect/8287d582-ef11-4b20-80fe-e648ab8e2bd5?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3Qi=
fQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU" rel style=3D"color: rgb(54,=
 55, 55); text-decoration: underline;">Resy</a></strong><span>. Before Eate=
r, people made reservations on OpenTable, a 1998-era product built for the =
desktop. &#8220;The advent of smartphones had come and gone without OpenTab=
le really doing anything to update the basic ideas of the product,&#8221; h=
e said on the </span><a href=3D"https://substack.com/redirect/284ae843-dbc2=
-4b60-8307-8bc6ae2beceb?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbq=
Osa8-6m8ExkRNpU" rel style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); text-decoration: unde=
rline;">Serious Eats podcast</a><span>. Resy embraced mobile, and won. He s=
old it to American Express in 2019.&#160;</span></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(=
54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span=
>After a couple of years inside of American Express, the $170 billion payme=
nts and loyalty behemoth, Ben started talking to some friends about what wa=
s next. One of those friends was </span><a href=3D"https://substack.com/red=
irect/3c68902b-6577-475d-a16b-72bbabfb815a?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7Gn=
A_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU" rel style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); te=
xt-decoration: underline;">Fred Wilson</a><span>, the Union Square Ventures=
 partner and early Coinbase investor. Ben had an idea around building somet=
hing in payments and loyalty for the restaurant industry, and Fred encourag=
ed him to consider building it onchain. He did, USV committed to co-lead an=
 $11 million financing alongside Shine Capital, and </span><strong><a href=
=3D"https://substack.com/redirect/69ec0fac-a340-4bf9-9d63-fe65887f52d5?j=3D=
eyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU" rel style=
=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); text-decoration: underline;">Blackbird</a></str=
ong><span> was born.&#160;</span></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); fo=
nt-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">Reading the last few=
 paragraphs, you might have picked up on a few themes.&#160;</p><p style=3D=
"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20=
px 0;">First, there&#8217;s the progression of products that mirrors the di=
ner&#8217;s journey. Discover a place to eat (Eater), make a reservation (R=
esy), enjoy the experience, pay, and come back (Blackbird).&#160;</p><p sty=
le=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0=
 0 20px 0;">Second, there&#8217;s the embrace of a new technology platform =
before anyone else in an industry. Eater replaced print with a blog on the =
internet. Resy replaced desktop (and the glued-together suite of reservatio=
n management &#8220;tools&#8221; like paper notes, spreadsheets, and emails=
) with a mobile app. Blackbird is replacing fragmented loyalty programs and=
 expensive payment systems with crypto rails.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: r=
gb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><s=
pan>In this and other ways, Blackbird is running the </span><strong>Ben Lev=
enthal Playbook</strong><span> with some new twists.&#160;</span></p><p sty=
le=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0=
 0 20px 0;"><span>There&#8217;s one big difference here, though. While Ben =
sold Eater and Resy to centralized companies, that&#8217;s not an option fo=
r Blackbird. Instead, </span><strong>ownership of the network of restaurant=
s will primarily go to the restaurants themselves</strong><span> as the com=
pany progressively decentralizes. &#8220;Overall, the restaurant industry s=
hould own roughly half of the network,&#8221; Ben told me.&#160;</span></p>=
<p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; mar=
gin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>That&#8217;s one of the things that&#8217;s newly p=
ossible because Blackbird uses crypto, but Blackbird works because it&#8217=
;s </span><em>not</em><span> a crypto app. It&#8217;s a restaurant platform=
 and consumer app, built by restaurant people, that only uses crypto and wh=
atever other tools it needs to use to make restaurants more profitable, hel=
p them understand their customers better, and build a healthier industry.&#=
160;</span></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-he=
ight: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">When I asked Ben what I couldn&#8217;t mis=
s in telling the Blackbird story, he said that they&#8217;re just really ex=
cited about the long term prospects for the industry.&#160;</p><p style=3D"=
color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20p=
x 0;">&#8220;We&#8217;re a couple of core unlocks away from a much better i=
ndustry.&#8221;&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16p=
x; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">This is a deep dive into the ind=
ustry and those unlocks.&#160;&#160;</p><h3 class=3D"header-anchor-post" st=
yle=3D"-moz-appearance: optimizelegibility; -moz-osx-font-smoothing: antial=
iased; -webkit-appearance: optimizelegibility; -webkit-font-smoothing: anti=
aliased; appearance: optimizelegibility; color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-famil=
y: 'SF Pro Display', -apple-system-headline, system-ui, -apple-system, Blin=
kMacSystemFont, 'Segoe UI', Roboto, Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif, 'Apple Co=
lor Emoji', 'Segoe UI Emoji', 'Segoe UI Symbol'; font-size: 1.375em; font-w=
eight: bold; line-height: 1.16em; margin: 1em 0 0.625em 0; position: relati=
ve;"><strong>How to Think About Blackbird</strong></h3><p style=3D"color: r=
gb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">Th=
ere are a few different ways to think about Blackbird. They&#8217;re all co=
nnected, but it&#8217;s worth unpacking them separately before bringing the=
m back together.&#160;&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-si=
ze: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>One way to think ab=
out Blackbird is from the </span><strong>industry perspective</strong><span=
>: as a tool to help restaurants drive better unit economics through paymen=
ts, loyalty, and customer insights.&#160;</span></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(=
54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span=
>A second way to think about Blackbird is from the </span><strong>diner per=
spective:</strong><span> as a way to discover&#160;somewhere to eat and get=
 magical, personalized dining experiences that scale alongside your loyalty=
=2E</span></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54,=
 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-heigh=
t: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>Another way to think about Blackbird is=
 as a </span><strong>business itself</strong><span>: as an onchain AmEx, si=
milar in many ways and different in a few important ones.&#160;</span></p><=
p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; marg=
in: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>A fourth way to think about Blackbird is as a </span=
><strong>blockchain network:</strong><span> as a decentralized platform tha=
t enables new forms of value creation and distribution in the restaurant ec=
osystem, and potentially, beyond it.&#160;</span></p><p style=3D"color: rgb=
(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">It&#=
8217;s all of those things, but to understand them, we need to start by und=
erstanding the restaurant business.</p><h3 class=3D"header-anchor-post" sty=
le=3D"-moz-appearance: optimizelegibility; -moz-osx-font-smoothing: antiali=
ased; -webkit-appearance: optimizelegibility; -webkit-font-smoothing: antia=
liased; appearance: optimizelegibility; color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-family=
: 'SF Pro Display', -apple-system-headline, system-ui, -apple-system, Blink=
MacSystemFont, 'Segoe UI', Roboto, Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif, 'Apple Col=
or Emoji', 'Segoe UI Emoji', 'Segoe UI Symbol'; font-size: 1.375em; font-we=
ight: bold; line-height: 1.16em; margin: 1em 0 0.625em 0; position: relativ=
e;"><strong>The Restaurant Business</strong></h3><p style=3D"color: rgb(54,=
 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">Restaura=
nts are one of those things that we don&#8217;t really want to think about =
as a business. Businesses need to make trade-offs. We don&#8217;t want rest=
aurants to make trade-offs. We want great food and great service every time=
 we walk in the door, because from our perspective, restaurants are an occa=
sion. They&#8217;re the rare chance to be taken care of, treated like royal=
ty, served. A little treat.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); fo=
nt-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">But, alas, restauran=
ts are a business, and their business model directly impacts the level of s=
ervice they&#8217;re able to provide.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 5=
5, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>When=
 Kevin Kwok wrote </span><em><a href=3D"https://substack.com/redirect/dc97e=
590-078a-4912-908b-86526dbd2abb?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjm=
lXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU" rel style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); text-decorati=
on: underline;">Aligning Business Models to Markets</a></em><span> in 2019,=
 he used a restaurant group, Danny Meyer&#8217;s Union Square Hospitality G=
roup (USHG), as his primary example.&#160;</span></p><p style=3D"color: rgb=
(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><spa=
n>USHG is undoubtedly one of the great success stories in the restaurant in=
dustry. Meyer made Union Square what it is today. </span><em>The Modern, Un=
ion Square Cafe, Manhatta</em><span>, </span><em>Gramercy Tavern,</em><span=
> </span><em>and ci siamo </em><span>rank consistently among New Yorkers&#8=
217; favorite places to eat. Shake Shack, which spun out of USHG, has a $3.=
4 billion market cap. In such a challenging industry, USHG&#8217;s consiste=
ncy stands out.&#160;</span></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-si=
ze: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>How does Danny do i=
t? Kwok explains: &#8220;In his business memoir </span><em><a href=3D"https=
://substack.com/redirect/ac23d615-8943-49ce-873a-fd541e081406?j=3DeyJ1IjoiO=
XAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU" rel style=3D"color: =
rgb(54, 55, 55); text-decoration: underline;">Setting the Table</a></em><sp=
an>, Meyer attributes his outsized success to an </span><strong>uncompromis=
ing focus on employees that leads to differentiated service.</strong><span>=
&#8221;</span></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line=
-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>So, Kwok asks, &#8220;If Danny Me=
yer&#8217;s employee-first approach is so effective, why haven&#8217;t we s=
een more restaurant groups adopting it faster? Or even more service-first a=
pproaches?&#8221; And answers, &#8220;</span><strong>Providing a high level=
 of service is a choice that must be supported by your business model</stro=
ng><span>.&#8221;&#160;</span></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-=
size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>I highly recommen=
d reading the </span><a href=3D"https://substack.com/redirect/dc97e590-078a=
