 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>You co=
uldn&#8217;t have built Blackbird onchain even five years ago. That&#8217;s=
 obvious. Which means that </span><strong>you couldn&#8217;t have built a p=
roduct like Blackbird even five years ago.</strong><span> That&#8217;s less=
 obvious, but more important.&#160;</span></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55=
, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><strong>Bla=
ckbird works because it&#8217;s able to perform like a normal consumer app =
while doing things that a normal consumer app can&#8217;t.</strong><span>&#=
160;</span></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-he=
ight: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>Let&#8217;s dive into a little bit a=
bout how Blackbird is structured under the hood, courtesy of the new </span=
><a href=3D"https://substack.com/redirect/6213f187-3bf4-4563-bb0c-f8f896789=
887?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU" rel=
 style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); text-decoration: underline;">Flypaper</a>=
<span>, to understand why and how.&#160;</span></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(5=
4, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>=
Earlier, I mentioned that Blackbird&#8217;s restaurant membership cards are=
 NFTs. They&#8217;re currently the only part of the app that&#8217;s onchai=
n, and it&#8217;s not very important that they&#8217;re onchain. For now, t=
hey&#8217;re non-transferrable (&#8220;</span><a href=3D"https://substack.c=
om/redirect/e8c0e61a-8a65-4a15-a616-9d4dba55e30b?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8=
J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU" rel style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 5=
5); text-decoration: underline;">we don&#8217;t think your identity is tran=
sferable</a><span>&#8221;) and can only be used within the Blackbird app. T=
hey could just as well be an entry in Blackbird&#8217;s database, for now, =
aside from the fact that if Blackbird disappeared tomorrow, I could walk in=
to Gjelina and show them that I do own my House Account NFT.&#160;</span></=
p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; m=
argin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>$FLY tokens </span><em>do</em><span> exist as ent=
ries in Blackbird&#8217;s database, for now. When you check-in to a restaur=
ant that offers $FLY for check-ins, Blackbird simply moves $FLY from the re=
staurant&#8217;s allocation to your account in its database. When you use $=
FLY to settle your tab with Blackbird Pay, it simply moves it from your acc=
ount&#8217;s to the restaurant&#8217;s in its database.&#160;</span></p><p =
style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin=
: 0 0 20px 0;">Going forward, $FLY will be used as an on-platform rewards a=
nd payments token, and restaurants will be able to exchange $FLY with Black=
bird at a pretty steady exchange rate. It won&#8217;t be tradeable, transfe=
rable, or redeemable for cash outside of the app. You won&#8217;t be able t=
o get rich speculating on $FLY.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55)=
; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">Blackbird users =
have speculated that, in addition to serving as a reward and payments token=
, $FLY would also serve as the gas token and representation of ownership in=
 the network once it moved onchain. That is not the case.&#160;</p><p style=
=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0=
 20px 0;"><span>Instead, the </span><a href=3D"https://substack.com/redirec=
t/6213f187-3bf4-4563-bb0c-f8f896789887?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_Zl=
NuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU" rel style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); text-d=
ecoration: underline;">Flypaper</a><span> introduces a new token, </span><s=
trong>$F2</strong><span>, which will serve as the gas and governance token =
for the network. The network itself will be a Layer 3, </span><strong>Flyne=
t</strong><span>, built on top of Coinbase&#8217;s Base L2 (which itself is=
 built on top of Ethereum). You don&#8217;t need to understand all of that,=
 just that it means a couple of things:</span></p><ol style=3D"margin-top: =
0; padding: 0;"><li style=3D"margin: 8px 0 0 32px;"><p style=3D"box-sizing:=
 border-box; color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; ma=
rgin: 0; margin-bottom: 0; padding-left: 4px;"><strong>Very fast, cheap tra=
nsactions</strong><span>. You won&#8217;t notice anything different than us=
ing a normal consumer app, and Blackbird Labs will cover a lot of the fees.=
&#160;</span></p></li><li style=3D"margin: 8px 0 0 32px;"><p style=3D"box-s=
izing: border-box; color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26=
px; margin: 0; margin-bottom: 0; padding-left: 4px;"><strong>Other Apps Can=
 Build on Flynet. </strong><span>If someone wanted to start a Blackbird for=
 airlines, as a dumb example, they could build it on Flynet and tap into $F=
LY for rewards and payments, and $F2 for gas.&#160;</span></p></li></ol><p =
style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin=
: 0 0 20px 0;">There will be a relationship between $FLY and $F2. When the =
chain launches, all $FLY balances that exist in Blackbird&#8217;s database =
will be moved onchain into users&#8217; Blackbird spending wallets on a 1:1=
 basis.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-=
height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>$F2 will be allocated to both dine=
rs and restaurants based on their </span><strong>$FLY throughput</strong><s=
pan> &#8211;&#160; the amount of $FLY they hold plus the amount of $FLY the=
y&#8217;ve burned by spending or redeeming rewards &#8211; divided by the t=
otal $FLY throughput on the network. If you somehow hold or have used 10% o=
f the $FLY on the network in a given period, you get 10% of that period&#82=
17;s $F2 allocation.&#160;</span></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); fo=
nt-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>This is a simp=
le and beautiful mechanism for distributing ownership in the network, and <=
/span><strong>one of the reasons that Blackbird couldn&#8217;t have been bu=
ilt offchain</strong><span>.</span></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); =
font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">First, network par=
ticipants (mainly diners and restaurants) will receive 251 million of the 5=
00 million total $F2 tokens, which means they&#8217;ll own and control a li=
ttle over half the network.</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-siz=
e: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">Second, because $F2 alloca=
tion within that 251 million tokens is measured by $FLY throughput, the res=
taurants and diners that are most active in the network will get more owner=
ship of the network.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size=
: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">Third, restaurants should n=
aturally earn more than diners given that most people can only eat at one r=
estaurant per night, and most restaurants can serve hundreds of people per =
night.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-h=
eight: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">Fourth, it incentivizes diners and restau=
rants to join the network and be active early. Since allocations are based =
on individual throughput over total network throughput, it will be easier t=
o earn more $F2 early. It&#8217;s an elegant way to get over the marketplac=
e cold start problem.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-siz=
e: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">And finally, because resta=
urants can reward diners with the $FLY it receives from Blackbird Labs in w=
ays they believe will help the restaurant, and because restaurants are phys=
ical, it will be impossible for bots to come in and sybil attack the networ=
k to steal all of the tokens. Any bot that wants to make an off-peak reserv=
ation at Principe, physically check-in, spend $500 with friends, and settle=
 the tab in $FLY to maximize their $FLY rewards is welcome to try.&#160;</p=
><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; ma=
rgin: 0 0 20px 0;">(Side note: I&#8217;d love to see the option to book har=
d-to-get reservations with $FLY.)</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); fo=
nt-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">Crypto makes diner a=
nd restaurant ownership of the network possible. It also makes instant, pra=
ctically-zero-fee payments via $FLY on Flynet possible. Those are core comp=
onents of what makes Blackbird special.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54,=
 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">Restaura=
nts and diners don&#8217;t need to spend one second thinking about crypto o=
r how any of it works behind the scenes.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54=
, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">As a re=
staurant, it&#8217;s worth thinking hard about how to design a loyalty prog=
ram that maximizes profitability, encourages the use of Blackbird Pay, and =
increases throughput. They might need to learn a little bit about digital a=
cquisition and retention tactics, but they don&#8217;t need to know anythin=
g about L2s or L3s.</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px;=
 line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>As a diner, you just need to=
 show up, check-in, enjoy, and leave. The same way some people work hard to=
 maximize their credit card points or airline miles, or </span><a href=3D"h=
ttps://substack.com/redirect/56932a7f-e6eb-4be0-b21a-962551159777?j=3DeyJ1I=
joiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU" rel style=3D"col=
or: rgb(54, 55, 55); text-decoration: underline;">set up bots to snipe rest=
aurant reservations</a><span>, some people will scheme to maximize their $F=
LY. Great. As long as the restaurants develop programs that are good for th=
e restaurant and the network, it&#8217;s a win-win. But diners won&#8217;t =
need to know a thing about crypto to get the &#8220;regular&#8221; experien=
ce at a growing number of restaurants.&#160;</span></p><p style=3D"color: r=
gb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">Cr=
ypto&#8217;s infrastructure is finally good enough that all of that can hap=
pen quietly and unnoticeably in the background. Jay pointed to two things i=
n particular that help power Blackbird&#8217;s surprisingly intuitive UX:&#=
160;</p><ol style=3D"margin-top: 0; padding: 0;"><li style=3D"margin: 8px 0=
 0 32px;"><p style=3D"box-sizing: border-box; color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-=
size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0; margin-bottom: 0; padding-left: 4=
px;"><strong><a href=3D"https://substack.com/redirect/58101e47-f53a-4cc9-89=
3b-b3bc92e7ade7?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8=
ExkRNpU" rel style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); text-decoration: underline;">=
Privy</a></strong><span> makes it easy to embed wallets that users control =
but don&#8217;t need to think about, right in the app.&#160;</span></p></li=
><li style=3D"margin: 8px 0 0 32px;"><p style=3D"box-sizing: border-box; co=
lor: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0; margin=
-bottom: 0; padding-left: 4px;"><strong><a href=3D"https://substack.com/red=
irect/e24b5c98-0d1d-4371-bd45-966221b69978?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7Gn=
A_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU" rel style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); te=
xt-decoration: underline;">Base</a></strong><span>, Coinbase&#8217;s EVM-Co=
mpatible Layer-2 network, is a cheap, highly performant L2 with the trusted=
 reputation and brand of Coinbase. (Since launching in August 2023, Base ha=
s already made upgrades that make the network cheaper and faster, which sho=
uld make onchain transactions so smooth that users won&#8217;t notice when =
more of Blackbird&#8217;s components move onchain).&#160;</span></p></li></=
ol><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; =
margin: 0 0 20px 0;">The result is that Blackbird can build a best-in-class=
 consumer app with superpowers. Programmable incentives. Faster, cheaper pa=
yments. Restaurant ownership and control.</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55,=
 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">And it means=
 that others besides Blackbird will be able to build similar products to fi=
x their industries.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size:=
 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>Fred Wilson pointed ou=
t that being onchain opens up the opportunity </span><strong>to build an Am=
Ex-like loyalty program where all the loyalty points are onchain.</strong><=
span>&#160;</span></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; =
line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">&#8220;$FLY is like a stablecoin. I=
t&#8217;s not something like Bitcoin where you buy it and hope it goes to $=
100k,&#8221; he said. &#8220;But the idea of taking loyalty points onchain =
is a big deal.&#8221;&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-siz=
e: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>Specifically, it wil=
l allow any application to embrace $FLY. &#8220;Right now,&#8221; said Fred=
, &#8220;AmEx and their partners are the only ones who can participate in A=
mEx points. But $FLY is like </span><a href=3D"https://substack.com/redirec=
t/a14a4046-fe24-4a56-a00e-50fc7d65278e?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_Zl=
NuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU" rel style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); text-d=
ecoration: underline;">USDC</a><span>: hopefully, in time, any developer wi=
ll be able to launch something that supports $FLY.&#8221;&#160;&#160;</span=
></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px=
; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">$FLY may become a rewards and payments token for all=
 sorts of merchants beyond restaurants. If an airline wanted to treat $FLY =
the same way they treat credit card points, for example, they might be able=
 to do that. If a luxury brand wanted to gate its new drop to only people w=
ho hold or have spent a certain amount of $FLY, they might be able to do th=
at, too.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line=
-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">The fun part, as always, is that develo=
pers and entrepreneurs will come up with much better ideas for how to use $=
FLY based on their own knowledge of what needs fixing, like Ben has for res=
taurants.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; lin=
e-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">To that end, Jay made a really interes=
ting point about why the a16z team got so excited about Blackbird,&#160; as=
ide from Ben himself. &#8220;Whenever there&#8217;s a huge market with a br=
oken business model, it&#8217;s a ripe opportunity for someone to try to fi=
x it with crypto.&#8221;&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-=
size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">Maybe, in Blackbird&#82=
17;s case, crypto really does fixes this, even if it does so behind the sce=
nes.</p><h3 class=3D"header-anchor-post" style=3D"-moz-appearance: optimize=
legibility; -moz-osx-font-smoothing: antialiased; -webkit-appearance: optim=
izelegibility; -webkit-font-smoothing: antialiased; appearance: optimizeleg=
ibility; color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-family: 'SF Pro Display', -apple-syst=
